A nagging feeling that ordinary people were long forgotten by their servants in postcolonial government has persisted for decades. However, there has always been someone to blame: foreign governments and their diabolical geopolitical machinations, multilateral institutions and their harebrained experiments, oppositionists and their treasonous agenda and the civil society on behalf of the neocolonial establishment.





But the African state incrementally milked, sucked and bled all sovereign power out of citizens, becoming autocratic and repressive in the name of protecting our freedom.
Every possible problem attracted violent responses through escalating police power. Surveillance, abduction and disappearance, torture and murder and, finally, imprisonment became normalised state responses to demands for services, explanation or accountability in the face of existential angst.
A monumentally corrupt, monstrously violent totalitarian state always consolidates itself to preside over corruption and repression in times of desperate citizen suffering. Obviously, this divides society into starkly opposed constituencies, with the state’s privileged surrogates living off the fat of the land, whilst the teeming mass of the Great Unwashed shiver in the sweltering fever of destitution. 



