Always, without fail, arrogant potentates make it their life’s purpose to strut and gloat, boastfully humiliating their victims with gratuitous insults.
In the independence years, a highly educated cosmopolitan endorsed Kenya’s ruthlessly exploitative and corrupt leadership, saying that a man-eat-man society is definitely better than a man-eat-nothing one. Shortly afterwards, a less refined colleague demanded the immediate detention of Karl Marx for misleading students to agitate for democracy.
In later years, surmising that protesting students loudly demanding dialogue were actually crying for chapati, another illustrious leader directed that the students must enjoy enough “dialogue” at all meal times. In turn, appreciative students were thenceforth expected to return to lecture halls, gladly bereft of the execrable Bwana Marx.
A legacy of these terrible times is the absolute death of critical engagement, robust intellectual flourishing and literary expression in our institutions of learning. The other was the relentless association of intellectual activity with basic subsistence, a sort of substitution of chapatti for discourse.



