Why are healthcare workers on strike, neglected, unappreciated and suffering unattended? Covid-19 pandemic’s official frontline combatants are not healthcare professionals, but the “securocracy”. 
The Ministry of Interior took charge of the situation and made the pandemic response a police affair, with the health bureaucracy reduced to incessant recital of barely meaningful statistics. 
Apart from co-ordinating development implementation, inspecting development projects and keeping contractors on toes, the Ministry of Interior is also eradicating gambling, ensuring that all learners are back in school on Monday and, one must infer, deploying orders to ensure that no coronavirus escapes the long arm of the law.
It also spearheads inter-ministerial committees and multiagency task forces to perform all sorts of transformational miracles.
Unsurprisingly, the most visible government activity today is essentially violent, with vulnerable citizens invariably on the receiving end.
Social distancing requirements of Covid-19 containment alone demand nearly threefold increment of school facilities. As matters stand, public schools have been dangerously overcrowded since government expanded transition without investing a single shilling in commensurate expansion of school infrastructure. 



