Ancient facilities are falling apart. Young Kenyans are penned in undignified, unsanitary and unsafe conditions. Schools are barely habitable, and there is yet no signal of meaningful government concern. 
Covid-19 demands extremely ambitious investment, which, clearly, is not forthcoming.
It is therefore perfectly in keeping with the temper of our time that Prof George Magoha would describe arrangements to learn under trees as innovative; the poor man is at his wits’ end. Any wonder then, that Wilson Sossion’s Knut is enduring a blistering revisiting?



